Business Brief -- CMS Enhancements Inc.:
   Company Is Studying Plans
   For a Major Restructuring
CMS Enhancements said it has about 440 employees
world-wide, including about 370 at its Irvine facilities. The
planned job terminations would affect various locations, the
spokesman said.
   CMS also announced that its chief financial officer and
treasurer, Frederick Judd, resigned effective tomorrow, to
pursue "personal business interests." He will be succeeded as
chief financial officer by Steven G. Holmes, a former Arthur
Andersen  Co. audit partner, CMS said. William Gibson,
controller, will assume some of Mr. Judd's other duties, the
company said. A new treasurer hasn't been named.
   For the year ended June 30, CMS Enhancements posted a net
loss of $8.5 million, or $2.89 a share, on sales of $130.1
million. In the first quarter of fiscal year 1992, the
company had a net loss of $894,000, or 30 cents a share, on
sales of $29.8 million.